Experiment 1- Solar Cell Construcon:
Biology perspecve:
Alexandre-Edmond Becquerel developed the
photovoltaic phenomenon in 1839. It uses the moon
of electrons to transform light, or photons, into
electricity. It is the underlying idea of solar energy and
is comparable to how plants use photosynthesis to
absorb sunlight energy.
Chemistry perspecve:
The basic parts of solar panels include cables, metal
components, semiconductors (typically silicon), and
other semiconductors. These components come
together to create a solar cell. The electrons in the
semiconductor become energized by sunlight striking
the solar cell, which causes the electrons to ow and
produce an electric current. Solar panels use this
technique to turn sunlight into electrical power.
Clean and Renewable Energy:
The process of creang a solar cell highlights the
signicance of scienc ideas as well as the benets
solar energy provides for the environment. Solar
energy is an eco-friendly and sustainable energy source
since it is clean, renewable, and uses the sun's energy
without harming the environment or depleng
essenal resources.
Reducing Greenhouse Gas Emissions:
The goal of the solar cell experiment is to have a
benecial impact rather than only study science. We
lessen our reliance on fossil fuels, which lowers
greenhouse gas emissions, by using solar cells and
eventually solar panels. This experiment shows how we
can use solar energy to power our future in a way that
is more sustainable and cleaner than nature does. Even
if it's a ny step, it could result in a big transformaon.
This experiment illustrates the basic concept of a
photovoltaic cell, where sunlight excites electrons,
creang an electric potenal.
The required materials to build a simple solar cell:
1-Copper sheet
2-Zinc sheet
3-Mulmeter
4-Sandpaper
5-Alligator clips
6-Saltwater soluon
7-Clear plasc container
There is a series of steps that you need to follow:
1)Cut the copper and zinc sheets into small squares.
Use sandpaper to clean the surfaces of the metal
squares.
2)Connect the copper and zinc squares to a mulmeter
using alligator clips.
3)Fill the clear plasc container with saltwater.
4)Submerge the metal squares into the saltwater
without leng them touch each other.
5)Observe the voltage generated on the mulmeter
when exposed to sunlight.
Experiment 2 – Biodiesel Producon:
What is meant by biodiesel producon:
The process of producing biodiesel fuel, an
environmentally responsible and renewable substute
for convenonal diesel fuel, is known as biodiesel
producon. Transestericaon is a chemical process
that turns discarded cooking oils, animal fats, or
vegetable oils into biodiesel. Using a catalyst, usually
methanol or ethanol, the triglycerides (fats and oils)
are transformed into biodiesel and glycerin during this
process.
Biology Perspecve:
The usage of fossil fuels in automobiles adds to both air
polluon and global warming. Greener and more
environmentally benecial is biodiesel, a biofuel
derived from natural sources like plants. Biofuels like
biodiesel are a beer opon for the environment,
much like trees purify the air.
Chemistry perspecve:
Composed of addives to make it engine-compable
and materials like vegetable oil biodiesel is a cleaner
fuel substute for convenonal diesel. Because it emits
fewer hazardous pollutants when used in automobiles
it is an environmentally benecial opon because it
results in less air polluon and greenhouse gas
emissions.
This experiment demonstrates how biodiesel, a
renewable and cleaner-burning fuel, can be synthesized
from vegetable oil through transestericaon.
The required materials are:
1- Vegetable oil
2-Methanol
3-Sodium hydroxide (lye)
4-Beakers
5-Safety goggles
6-Srring rod
7-Measuring equipment
There is a series of steps that you need to follow:
1)In a well-venlated area and while wearing safety
goggles, carefully mix methanol and sodium hydroxide
to create methoxide (a chemical catalyst).
2)Add the methoxide to the vegetable oil in a beaker.
3)Sr the mixture vigorously for about an hour.
4)Allow the mixture to sele; two layers will form.
5)The top layer is biodiesel, and the boom layer is
glycerin. Carefully separate the biodiesel.
Experiment 3 Water electrolysis for Hydrogen
Producon:
What is meant by electrolysis:
Electrolysis of water is using electricity to split water
into oxygen and hydrogen gas by electrolysis. Hydrogen
gas released in this way can be used as hydrogen fuel,
but must be kept apart from the oxygen as the mixture
would be extremely explosive.
Biology perspecve:
Water electrolysis is a process that divides water into
hydrogen and water, just like how plants separate
water in photosynthesis. Hydrogen also serves as a eco-
friendly fuel.
Chemistry perspecve:
Electricity divides water into hydrogen and oxygen.
Hydrogen is important because it can power fuel cells
that generate electricity without aecng the
environment.
This experiment demonstrates the electrolysis of water
to produce hydrogen and oxygen gases, showcasing the
potenal of hydrogen as a clean fuel.
The required materials are:
1-Two pencils
2-Two alligator clips
3-Two small jars or cups
4-Salt
5-Water
There is a series of steps that you need to follow:
1)Fill the jars with water and add a pinch of salt to
each.
2)Submerge the eraser ends of the pencils in the water.
3)Connect the pencils to a power source (e.g., a 9-volt
baery) using alligator clips.
4)Observe bubbles forming at the pencil electrodes.
5)Test the gases by lighng a splint and placing it near
the bubbles.

What is meant by global warming?
Global warming is the long-term increase in Earth's
average temperature due to the buildup of greenhouse
gases in the atmosphere, primarily from human
acvies like burning fossil fuels. This leads to
environmental and climac changes with various
consequences.
What is meant by air polluon:
Air polluon is the contaminaon of the air by harmful
substances, such as chemicals, parculate maer, and
gases, which can have adverse eects on human
health, the environment, and the quality of the air we
breathe.
Discussion on Global Warming and Air Polluon:
Biology perspecve:
Global warming as if the Earth is having a fever due to
an excess of heat-trapping substances in the air. Air
polluon, caused by sources like cars and factories,
dires the air and can harm our health, much like
smoky air. Plants and trees naturally clean the air, but
human acvies can impede their eorts.
Chemistry perspecve:
Global warming occurs when we combust fossil fuels
such as coal and gas, releasing gases like carbon dioxide
that trap heat in the atmosphere. The polluted air
resulng from burning these fuels contains harmful
parcles and gases.
Consequences of Air Polluon:
Environmental consequences:
1- Damage to Ecosystems: Wildlife, aquac habitats,
and plant life are all impacted by air polluon. It may
upset ecosystems' natural equilibrium, which would
reduce biodiversity.
2- Acid Rain: Acid rain can result from air polluon,
parcularly from nitrogen oxides and sulfur dioxide.
This may harm freshwater ecosystems, soil, and forests,
which may have an impact on aquac and plant life.
3- Ozone Depleon: The decline of the ozone layer can
be caused by some air pollutants, such as
chlorouorocarbons (CFCs), which shield humans from
ultraviolet light.
Health consequences:
1- Respiratory Problems: lung diseases like bronchis,
asthma, and chronic obstrucve pulmonary disease
(COPD) can be brought on by or made worse by air
polluon.
2- Cardiovascular Issues: Connuous exposure to air
polluon has been related to a higher risk of heart-
related condions, such as heart aacks and strokes.
3-cancer: Certain air pollutants, specically
formaldehyde and benzene, are categorized as
carcinogens and have the potenal to cause cancer,
especially lung cancer.
4- Reduced Lung Funcon: Children who are exposed
to air polluon may have delayed lung development
and funcon, which could have long-term eects on
their health.
5- Premature Death: Early death is associated with air
polluon. Due to health issues linked to polluon,
individuals of locaons with high polluon levels are
more likely to die young.
Impact of Global warming:
Global warming, which is primarily driven by the
increase in greenhouse gases in the Earth's
atmosphere, has far-reaching and oen adverse
impacts on the planet. Here are some examples of the
Impacts of Global Warming:
1- Rising Temperatures: Heatwaves are becoming
increasingly oen and powerful due to rising global
average temperatures, parcularly in urban areas.
Heat-related illnesses and even deaths may arise from
this.
2- Melng Ice and Glaciers: Sea levels rise because of
the melng of polar ice caps and glaciers brought on by
warmer temperatures. Ecosystems and coastal
communies are at risk from this.
3-Rising Sea Levels: Sea levels are increasing as ice
melts and seawater expands because of global
warming. Communies that may be demolished
ooding may occur, and coastal erosion may result
from this.
4-Ocean Acidicaon: The seas get more acidic
because of increased atmospheric carbon dioxide (CO2)
dissolving in them. This may be harmful to marine life,
especially shellsh and coral reefs.
5-Extreme Weather Events: Hurricanes, droughts,
oods, and wildres are among the more common and
severe weather phenomena that are linked to global
warming. Both property and lives may be lost because
of these incidents.
